The stress is laid on the dei cation; death, as a necessary preliminary, is lost to sight. ‘ Bibit: however, which makes Augustus a ‘praesens deus‚' al- ready living on earth the lise of a god, is more in accordance with Horace's usual language ; see especially Od. 4. 5. 31-36‚ and the passage already quoted from Epp. 2. 1. 15 foll. ⁴ Praesenti tibi maturos largimur honores Iurandasque tuum per nomen ponimus aras.' It is more likely also to have been altered, as the more extravagant, especially to ears familiar with the Christian concep- tion of life aster death. But Horace's own transfiguration in Od. 2. 20, and the beatification given by the Muse to Romulus and Hercules and the Dioscuri in 4. 8 are metaphors of fame, not forms of a future lise.
